$MSTR is the undisputed king of #Bitcoin corporate treasuries. There is no second best.

But could there be a second best someday?

Possibly, but there is an enormous hurdle to overcome, and it's not a financial problem, but a marketing problem. Let me explain.

Positioning

In their seminal marketing book of the same name, Al Ries and Jack Trout introduced the concept of "Positioning."

Positioning is essentially the way a product or brand differentiates itself from competitors.

The textbook example of positioning is Coca-Cola vs. Pepsi. Coke positions itself as the original cola, whereas Pepsi is the "challenger" and its marketing emphasizes youthful energy, excitement, and rebellion.

MicroStrategy's positioning is "leveraged bitcoin." When you buy MicroStrategy stock, you're buying Michael Saylor's unwavering commitment to acquiring as much Bitcoin as possible as quickly as possible.

Your decision to buy $MSTR might be influenced by charts and numbers, but the mere numeric case for returns is not fundamentally what drives fandom of the company.

There is no significant number two player. There is no Pepsi to MicroStrategy's Coke.

First Mover Advantage

Typically, the first product in a category dominates the category. It can even become synonymous with the category. Think of Kleenex, Band-Aids, and Velcro.

Likewise, we talk about any company starting a Bitcoin treasury today as "running the MicroStrategy playbook."

#MetaPlanet has been literally dubbed "The MicroStrategy of Japan." 

Positioning Against the Leader

This is only the beginning of the positioning problems for new adopters of Bitcoin treasuries.

Even before we get to their market share, it's not clear what "mindshare" they will occupy. "Me too" is not a strong foundation to build on.

Compounding the problem, the way I see investment cases presented for these companies often looks more like special situation investing with a one-time pop rather than an enduring value proposition.

Typical market structure and human mind space converges on only 3 major brands in a product category.

For major second and third place players in the Bitcoin corporate treasury space to emerge, companies will not only need to successfully execute strategies for acquiring enough bitcoin to secure their rankings, but also clearly differentiate their positioning.

Possible Positioning Strategies

If MicroStrategy is "leveraged bitcoin," perhaps another company could be "3x leveraged bitcoin."

There would be practical problems making "3x leveraged bitcoin" positioning a reality, but the general principle is that there needs to be a clear rationale why you would allocate part of your portfolio to the other stock in order for it to capture market share.

I.e., if you want leveraged Bitcoin buy $MSTR, if you want 3x leveraged Bitcoin buy stock XYZ.

Of current companies implementing Bitcoin treasuries, MetaPlanet has the strongest positioning. Even though "The MicroStrategy of Japan" has a "me too" ring to it, it still establishes a clear niche in Japan that makes sense because of the geographical practicalities of investing.

Bullish on Bitcoin Corporate Treasuries

Despite challenges with positioning, I am enormously bullish on the potential for Bitcoin as a treasury asset to add value for companies and investors.

It's already too late for any company to catch up with MicroStrategy for the number one spot, but number two and three are still up for grabs.

I'm massively rooting for companies like $SMLR to carve out their own niche in the space.

That said, not every company needs to popularize itself as a Bitcoin proxy in order to benefit from holding Bitcoin in its treasury. There is no second best treasury asset.
